A:

I'm not sure what you are talking about, but I think you are asking about the behavior of the for-loop.
Certainly, the for-loop is a loop, but it's a loop that starts on the first iteration.
Consider this code:
for(int i = 0; i < 100; i++)
{
    for(int x = 0; x < 100; x++)
    {
        for(int y = 0; y < 100; y++)
        {
            if(i % 2 == 0)
            {
                ++x;
            }

            if(i % 2 == 1)
            {
                ++y;
            }
        }
    }
}

Now, consider what happens if you change it to this:
for(int x = 0; x < 100; x++)
{
    for(int y = 0; y < 100; y++)
    {
        if(i % 2 == 0)
        {
            ++x;
        }

        if(i % 2 == 1)
        {
            ++y;
        }
    }
}

Now, consider what happens if you change it to this:
for(int x = 0; x < 100; x++)
{
    for(int y = 0; y < 100; y++)
    {
        if(i % 2 == 0)
        {
            ++x;
        }

        if(i % 2 == 1)
        {
            ++y;
        }
    }
}

Now, you have a loop that starts on the first iteration and loops 100 times.



