A:

If you want to try to make it work, you can change the constraints of the 2D array to be a matrix.
int array[9][9];
for (int i = 0; i < 9; i++)
{
    for (int j = 0; j < 9; j++)
    {
        if (i == j) // don't copy the same object twice
        {
            continue;
        }
        array[i][j] = 0;
    }
}

If you want to not get the weird bug, where the program hangs and nothing happens when you press the mouse, you can try to change the array to a boolean array.
bool array[9][9];
for (int i = 0; i < 9; i++)
{
    for (int j = 0; j < 9; j++)
    {
        if (i == j) // don't copy the same object twice
        {
            continue;
        }

        array[i][j] = true;
    }
}

It is not guaranteed that this will work perfectly, but it should work.

A mind is a terrible thing to waste. When you have something you really want,
you have to force it. So I forced it.

Monday, September 21, 2010

One of the most amazing things is that I am now part of a "team" that is working on the ultimate project in the world. This is not a team of people working on one thing, but a team of people who are building a "company," and who have an awesome product to show for it.

I am part of the team that is building the ultimate camera. It is called the M-DVR, and it is the first consumer-grade DVR system to be sold in the United States. There is an M-DVR selling for $199 on Amazon.com.

The M-DVR is different than other DVRs, because it does not record too much. It records about two hours of footage. It records all the day's footage, and it records the night's footage as well. Also, the M-DVR can record to a computer. You don't need a computer to record to a M-DVR. You can record from the M-DVR to your computer using an infrared cable.

